        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Yes. It is not easy. Especially, in TUI it is impossible.\r\n\r\nThere is [im-select](https://github.com/daipeihust/im-select) for Windows and macOS, which works under TUI. On Linux desktop, `gdbus` or `fcitx-remote` can be used for the corresponding iBus or Fcitx IM framework. However, there is no reliable way on Linux to detect which IM framework is used by the current desktop environment.\r\n\r\nThe best thing I can think of is that, Neovim provides API to customize how to switch IM.\r\n\r\nI used to implement [a plugin](https://github.com/brglng/vim-im-select) for Vim/Neovim, which calls `im-select` on `InsertLeave` and `InsertEnter`. However it is better for Vim/Neovim to support this feature in the core, because if a plugin tries to implement IM switching for search mode, it will have to remap keys like `f` `F` `t` `T`, but those keys are often already remapped by some other plugins, or by the user.",
